00:03:56.341 --> 00:03:57.739
What is ARIA?

00:03:58.906 --> 00:04:03.271
The abbreviation means
"Accessible Rich Internet Applications"

00:04:03.616 --> 00:04:07.521
You can forget that right away,
but what you need to know is…

00:04:08.960 --> 00:04:12.034
ARIA are attributes—

00:04:12.975 --> 00:04:17.657
HTML5 attributes that give
extra information and feedback

00:04:17.682 --> 00:04:21.694
to assistive technology, like,
for example, screen readers.

00:04:23.462 --> 00:04:26.875
In forms you can use it
for naming form controls,

00:04:27.416 --> 00:04:29.726
describing extra information,

00:04:30.159 --> 00:04:33.310
and for giving feedback on dynamic changes.

00:04:34.159 --> 00:04:38.128
I will give you examples
of that in the demos later.

00:04:39.731 --> 00:04:47.207
Before you start, you need to know:
the first rule of ARIA is don't use ARIA.

00:04:47.722 --> 00:04:49.639
There are five rules—

00:04:49.663 --> 00:04:52.052
go and look them up when you have time—

00:04:52.076 --> 00:04:54.326
but the first rule is the most important.

00:04:55.119 --> 00:04:59.461
Don't use ARIA to fix
meaningless and incorrect HTML5,

00:05:00.059 --> 00:05:02.852
use the already available elements,

00:05:02.877 --> 00:05:04.250
because then the browser

00:05:04.275 --> 00:05:07.930
and the screen reader knows how
to operate and understand them.

00:05:08.908 --> 00:05:13.082
ARIA is about feedback not about fixing.

00:05:14.661 --> 00:05:18.352
If you want to join me
or look up the code later,

00:05:19.343 --> 00:05:30.159
the example code is on
https://lvl.li/aria-in-forms.

00:05:30.985 --> 00:05:34.922
These examples contain
very simplified forms,

00:05:35.295 --> 00:05:37.679
and before you start nagging,

00:05:37.703 --> 00:05:41.965
no data is submitted;
no security checks; no translation;

00:05:42.647 --> 00:05:47.352
I just want to show you what happens
in the front end, so you get the ARIA.

00:05:51.190 --> 00:05:53.607
I will do the demos in Safari.

00:05:53.631 --> 00:05:58.063
It's the browser works best together
with the VoiceOver screen reader.

00:05:59.254 --> 00:06:03.186
First, I'll talk you through how
to properly name form controls,

00:06:04.297 --> 00:06:08.226
and we're going to look at the
accessibility tree, to show how that works.

00:06:09.479 --> 00:06:11.737
And then we're going to
look at two different forms

00:06:11.761 --> 00:06:13.518
and add descriptions and feedback.

00:06:15.137 --> 00:06:17.252
For all the people expecting me to show

00:06:17.276 --> 00:06:20.872
how to build new web
components from scratch with ARIA,

00:06:21.200 --> 00:06:25.727
I'll share at the end of this talk,
my opinion about going fancy in forms.

00:06:26.240 --> 00:06:28.854
Naming and describing form controls.

00:06:30.854 --> 00:06:32.250
Let's do that.

00:06:36.846 --> 00:06:41.890
Before you use ARIA, you have to
have the basics in order.

00:06:42.335 --> 00:06:45.930
The basics—the basic HTML5 must be correct.

00:06:46.985 --> 00:06:51.530
And then it's super important that
you give your form control a name,

00:06:53.206 --> 00:06:55.253
an accessible name.

00:06:56.364 --> 00:06:59.100
Okay. I will show you how
that works for a screen reader.

00:06:59.663 --> 00:07:03.830
Here we have a label, "your question,"
and a textarea.

00:07:05.377 --> 00:07:06.437
If you can see,

00:07:06.461 --> 00:07:11.732
you can see the label is
put above the form control

00:07:13.312 --> 00:07:16.153
—perfectly understandable.

00:07:18.560 --> 00:07:22.202
But the label is not
connected to the form control,

00:07:22.972 --> 00:07:26.162
so a screen reader doesn't
know what to announce here.

00:07:26.774 --> 00:07:30.067
You have to connect the
label to the form control,

00:07:30.092 --> 00:07:32.897
and you can do that with a label

00:07:32.921 --> 00:07:38.462
"for" is pointing to the
"id" of the form control.

00:07:38.487 --> 00:07:43.080
Here, the textarea has
an ID of "id-textarea".

00:07:44.179 --> 00:07:48.180
So the label has a "for" is "id-textarea"

00:07:49.641 --> 00:07:51.760
Now they are connected.

00:07:52.880 --> 00:07:57.369
I will start the screen reader and
let you hear how important that is.

00:07:59.115 --> 00:08:01.044
Okay, start VoiceOver.

00:08:05.600 --> 00:08:10.060
<v VoiceOver>VoiceOver on Safari. Naming and
describing form controls, window, toolbar.

00:08:10.766 --> 00:08:17.770
<v Rian>Okay. When a screen reader
enters a form, they jump into "form mode."

00:08:18.969 --> 00:08:24.563
That gives the user the opportunity to type
instead of operating the screen reader.

00:08:24.865 --> 00:08:29.368
and then you can jump with tab key from
focusable element to focusable element.

00:08:30.050 --> 00:08:33.528
So, I'll tab now in the first form control.

00:08:33.553 --> 00:08:34.580
<v VoiceOver>Leaving toolbar.

00:08:34.604 --> 00:08:37.408
Entering Naming and describing
form controls web content.

00:08:37.433 --> 00:08:40.216
Edit text, blank, main.

00:08:41.756 --> 00:08:49.700
<v Rian>About the form field textarea,
it announces "edit text, blank."

00:08:51.471 --> 00:08:53.919
So, it is an edit text field.

00:08:53.943 --> 00:08:56.205
"Blank" is "I have no name."

00:08:57.026 --> 00:09:01.375
If I tab to the next one, that
has a "for" and "id" connection:

00:09:01.936 --> 00:09:03.509
<v VoiceOver>Your question, edit text.

00:09:04.184 --> 00:09:07.099
<v Rian>Then it says "your question, edit text."

00:09:07.583 --> 00:09:11.107
And then a screen reader
user knows what to fill out.

00:09:11.630 --> 00:09:14.885
So without a connection
<v VoiceOver>"edit text. blank."</v>

00:09:15.449 --> 00:09:18.390
<v Rian>With a connection? </v>
<v VoiceOver>"Your question, edit text."</v>

00:09:19.354 --> 00:09:22.312
<v Rian>Okay. That must be in order.

00:09:24.153 --> 00:09:27.586
You have to have a
name for the form control.

00:09:28.256 --> 00:09:30.589
Okay, you can use a placeholder then.

00:09:31.677 --> 00:09:35.225
Is a placeholder a replacement for a label?

00:09:35.249 --> 00:09:36.462
No, it isn't,

00:09:37.640 --> 00:09:40.430
But screen readers get smarter and smarter.

00:09:40.454 --> 00:09:45.504
In this case, I have a textarea
with a placeholder, "your question."

00:09:45.529 --> 00:09:47.982
Let's listen how that sounds.

00:09:48.006 --> 00:09:50.541
<v VoiceOver>"Your question,
edit text, blank."

00:09:53.407 --> 00:09:54.685
Your question

00:09:55.906 --> 00:09:59.277
<v Rian>So the screen reader
announces "your question," the placeholder,

00:09:59.817 --> 00:10:02.353
and then tries to figure
out what's the name.

00:10:02.377 --> 00:10:05.139
Cannot come up with
the name, so it guesses,

00:10:05.163 --> 00:10:07.123
okay, the placeholder must be the name.

00:10:08.615 --> 00:10:13.861
Not all screen readers do this, so
don't depend on this always working.

00:10:16.631 --> 00:10:18.904
There's also another issue with this.

00:10:20.293 --> 00:10:23.195
The placeholder text
disappears when you start typing,

00:10:23.219 --> 00:10:26.444
or when the field is filled
out with an autocomplete.

00:10:27.830 --> 00:10:30.620
People may forget what to fill out,

00:10:30.644 --> 00:10:34.481
or need to check if the right
value is added to the right fields

00:10:34.505 --> 00:10:35.826
with an autocomplete.

00:10:36.754 --> 00:10:40.841
Always add a visual
label to prevent errors.

00:10:45.198 --> 00:10:48.591
So the next thing you can do with ARIA is

00:10:48.615 --> 00:10:52.927
give a form control a
name with an "aria-label."

00:10:53.600 --> 00:10:57.203
In this case, textarea,
aria-label "your question."

00:10:58.220 --> 00:10:59.902
If I tab into this,

00:10:59.927 --> 00:11:01.648
<v VoiceOver>Your question, edit text.

00:11:01.679 --> 00:11:06.479
<v Rian>It's announced perfectly well,
but there's no visual label.

00:11:10.233 --> 00:11:13.332
You can have a
placeholder and an aria-label:

00:11:13.984 --> 00:11:16.484
<v VoiceOver>Your question,
edit text, describe your question.

00:11:17.912 --> 00:11:22.096
<v Rian> The placeholder is announced in
a different voice, "describe your question"

00:11:22.683 --> 00:11:25.636
and aria-label is "your question,"

00:11:26.525 --> 00:11:29.096
but still you have no visual label.

00:11:31.899 --> 00:11:34.963
You can use an "aria-labelledby."

00:11:36.526 --> 00:11:43.693
Instead of the element "label," you
can use, for example, a "div". Yay, a div.

00:11:46.000 --> 00:11:51.817
But you have to connect both together,
and that you do with "aria-labelledby."

00:11:52.111 --> 00:11:55.515
You give the div an "id"

00:11:56.440 --> 00:12:03.813
and in the form control textarea
you say labeled by referring to that id.

00:12:05.863 --> 00:12:07.359
How is that announced?

00:12:07.383 --> 00:12:09.383
<v VoiceOver>Your question, edit text.

00:12:09.407 --> 00:12:10.744
<v Rian>Perfectly okay.

00:12:11.315 --> 00:12:15.129
I have no idea why you should
use a div instead of a label,

00:12:15.154 --> 00:12:20.244
but maybe you have some
obscure use case for this.

00:12:23.762 --> 00:12:29.171
Next one. "aria-describedby,"
and this is super useful.

00:12:30.778 --> 00:12:33.522
As I told you, you jump into form mode

00:12:36.506 --> 00:12:44.274
and then, you only get announced
what is connected to the form control.

00:12:45.528 --> 00:12:49.064
So in this case, if you
have your new password,

00:12:49.088 --> 00:12:51.432
and you have an input for your password,

00:12:52.048 --> 00:12:57.333
and below that, the rules "please use a
password of minimal eight characters,"

00:12:57.881 --> 00:13:00.853
that also must be
connected to the input field.

00:13:00.878 --> 00:13:03.385
Otherwise, the screen
reader doesn't announce it,

00:13:03.410 --> 00:13:07.338
because the screen reader
doesn't know it's connected.

00:13:08.631 --> 00:13:11.240
And that you do with aria-describedby.

00:13:13.588 --> 00:13:17.913
The paragraph with extra
information, you give that an id,

00:13:18.787 --> 00:13:23.610
and in the input field, the form
control, you say aria-describedby

00:13:23.635 --> 00:13:25.579
referring to that id.

00:13:26.360 --> 00:13:30.188
<v VoiceOver>Your new password,
secure edit text with autofill menu.

00:13:33.063 --> 00:13:35.402
Please use a password
of minimal 8 characters.

00:13:36.558 --> 00:13:41.633
<v Rian>You notice there is a time
lapse between announcing the label

00:13:41.657 --> 00:13:45.976
and announcing the
aria-describedby information,

00:13:46.246 --> 00:13:48.592
that's a safari issue.

00:13:48.683 --> 00:13:51.166
[Unintelligible]

00:13:51.191 --> 00:13:54.099
...update which will solve it, soon

00:13:55.198 --> 00:13:59.673
but now you first hear the label and
then you hear the aria-describedby

00:13:59.714 --> 00:14:02.857
so you get all the information
you need with a form control.

00:14:03.239 --> 00:14:05.088
Next topic: icons.

00:14:06.373 --> 00:14:07.973
How do you announce an icon?

00:14:09.111 --> 00:14:12.879
Which of course the screen
reader cannot know what's in an icon.

00:14:14.482 --> 00:14:20.492
Well, in this form you have a label with
a search, an input field, and a button.

00:14:21.108 --> 00:14:23.231
And the button has a class,

00:14:24.226 --> 00:14:29.122
that Fontawesome class displays
an icon of a search, a loop.

00:14:30.407 --> 00:14:33.993
If can see this, it's perfectly okay,

00:14:34.018 --> 00:14:36.240
but how does this announce?

00:14:36.902 --> 00:14:38.371
<v VoiceOver>Search, edit text.

00:14:38.891 --> 00:14:39.923
[silence]

00:14:40.188 --> 00:14:42.809
<v Rian>If I give the button focus I hear nothing.

00:14:44.584 --> 00:14:47.830
So I have to give
the button a name.

00:14:51.280 --> 00:14:54.014
And that you can do with aria-label.

00:14:54.039 --> 00:14:56.646
aria-label, "Submit search."

00:14:57.541 --> 00:14:58.981
you put that on the button.

00:15:00.263 --> 00:15:05.923
all the content inside the button is
omitted, only the aria-label is announced.

00:15:06.725 --> 00:15:08.541
Now, let's see what it does.

00:15:09.084 --> 00:15:10.505
<v VoiceOver>Search, edit text.

00:15:11.341 --> 00:15:12.395
[Silence]

00:15:12.481 --> 00:15:13.926
<v Rian>I still hear nothing!</v>

00:15:14.438 --> 00:15:16.873
that's weird! I put an aria-label on it.

00:15:18.919 --> 00:15:20.738
I will mute the screen reader now.

00:15:23.479 --> 00:15:26.127
And now, I'm going to inspect the code.

00:15:28.754 --> 00:15:34.919
And then, I see button,
class: "font-awesome",

00:15:35.437 --> 00:15:37.590
aria-label "submit search"

00:15:37.614 --> 00:15:41.853
and then font awesome
added "aria-hidden" is true to it.

00:15:43.519 --> 00:15:47.357
That's because font awesome thinks,

00:15:47.381 --> 00:15:50.794
"Okay, if it's an icon, better
hide it from screen readers,

00:15:50.819 --> 00:15:52.588
because they cannot pronounce it."

00:15:54.378 --> 00:15:59.411
But if you put a font awesome
icon directly on a focusable element,

00:15:59.436 --> 00:16:01.603
on an element that really makes sense,

00:16:03.522 --> 00:16:05.600
and you put an aria-hidden, true, on that,

00:16:05.600 --> 00:16:08.941
the screen reader doesn't
know what it is. It omits it,

00:16:08.966 --> 00:16:10.917
It thinks, "Okay, it doesn't exist."

00:16:12.734 --> 00:16:14.447
What's the workaround for that?

00:16:18.562 --> 00:16:24.449
You move the class of the font
awesome class out of the button—

00:16:24.474 --> 00:16:27.100
oh, actually, you move
it inside the button.

00:16:27.846 --> 00:16:31.211
in a span and you
give the class to a span.

00:16:32.727 --> 00:16:35.459
So the button has the aria-label only,

00:16:35.943 --> 00:16:41.237
and the span with the font awesome
class with the loop icon is inside,

00:16:41.551 --> 00:16:43.035
and it's in the span.

00:16:44.987 --> 00:16:48.848
That way, the label—
aria-label is announced.

00:16:49.396 --> 00:16:51.222
Now, let's see what...

00:16:53.165 --> 00:16:54.559
I'll close this.

00:16:55.729 --> 00:16:58.350
So let's move from the start.

00:16:59.573 --> 00:17:01.017
<v VoiceOver>Search, edit text.

00:17:02.105 --> 00:17:03.115
[Silence]

00:17:03.160 --> 00:17:04.410
<v Rian>You hear nothing.</v>

00:17:04.435 --> 00:17:06.374
<v VoiceOver>Search, edit text.

00:17:07.204 --> 00:17:09.093
<v Rian>Scroll up a bit,
[Silence]

00:17:09.118 --> 00:17:10.443
You hear nothing,

00:17:10.483 --> 00:17:13.268
and then, with the span inside the button,

00:17:13.293 --> 00:17:14.753
<v VoiceOver>Search, edit text,

00:17:15.070 --> 00:17:16.642
Submit search, button.

00:17:16.705 --> 00:17:18.350
<v Rian>Then the button is announced.

00:17:18.374 --> 00:17:19.996
Okay. Keep this in mind:

00:17:21.139 --> 00:17:25.512
not every—this aria-hidden
is generated by font awesome

00:17:25.537 --> 00:17:28.417
so, don't put it on an element
that needs to be announced,

00:17:28.442 --> 00:17:29.764
that needs to have a label,

00:17:30.027 --> 00:17:32.153
because it will be hidden.

00:17:36.400 --> 00:17:41.923
You can actually check what the
accessible name is for a form control

00:17:42.444 --> 00:17:44.587
by checking the accessibility tree.

00:17:45.452 --> 00:17:48.392
Each browser generates
an accessibility tree,

00:17:48.702 --> 00:17:53.960
and screen readers, or assistive technology,
actually read that accessibility tree

00:17:53.984 --> 00:17:58.763
to know what to announce and
how to operate a form control.

00:18:01.009 --> 00:18:03.572
I will show you in Chrome and in Firefox.

00:18:04.398 --> 00:18:05.787
This is the one in Chrome.

00:18:07.734 --> 00:18:08.896
I will inspect.

00:18:11.103 --> 00:18:16.189
And here, I chose the textarea
without connected label.

00:18:19.726 --> 00:18:23.678
And… wait a sec…

00:18:23.703 --> 00:18:28.139
I can check the tab "accessibility"

00:18:28.915 --> 00:18:30.755
and here's the accessibility tree,

00:18:31.993 --> 00:18:34.589
and then you can check out the name.

00:18:34.842 --> 00:18:40.261
So, when there's no connection between
the textarea and the label, it has no name.

00:18:40.824 --> 00:18:43.241
and it cannot find any name,

00:18:43.265 --> 00:18:50.679
in, for example, the title, the
placeholder, aria-label, aria-labelledby,

00:18:51.116 --> 00:18:54.259
[unintelligible]

00:18:54.320 --> 00:18:57.630
So this form control
has no accessible name.

00:18:57.662 --> 00:19:02.129
If we check the next one,
with the for/id construction,

00:19:02.560 --> 00:19:04.737
it has name "your question"

00:19:05.518 --> 00:19:10.195
and the name comes from the label,
and the label is "your question."

00:19:12.110 --> 00:19:14.187
Next one: placeholder.

00:19:21.120 --> 00:19:24.571
Name is "your question," and
it gets it from the placeholder.

00:19:25.897 --> 00:19:28.588
This is a screen reader workaround.

00:19:31.468 --> 00:19:33.104
Aria-label.

00:19:38.342 --> 00:19:41.373
Name is "your question" and
it gets it from the aria-label.

