00:38:20.997 --> 00:38:24.305
<v Rian>Now the screen
reader gets—user gets feedback!

00:38:24.623 --> 00:38:27.614
This can do with some styling, I know.

00:38:27.920 --> 00:38:30.210
But this is the principle, how it works.

00:38:31.488 --> 00:38:36.341
In WordPress, we have a very
elegant way to add aria-live to your code

00:38:36.821 --> 00:38:40.970
They are not depending on
elements being in the DOM or not.

00:38:42.430 --> 00:38:49.420
It's a JavaScript method
called "wp.a11y.speak,"

00:38:50.825 --> 00:38:53.286
and it's included into WordPress core.

00:38:53.618 --> 00:38:59.069
There is documentation on how to do it
on the accessibility handbook of WordPress.

00:38:59.094 --> 00:39:05.415
That's on
make.wordpress.org/accessibility/handbook.

00:39:06.296 --> 00:39:09.046
And there, with the
development best practices,

00:39:09.407 --> 00:39:13.310
there's a chapter about wp.a11y.speak.

